d Cumberland): variant of   Crone  .","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Kron   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. The surname <i>Cron</i> is also found in France (Alsace).","French (western): probably from <i>crone</i>, a regional word denoting a water hole, hence a nickname for someone who fishes in the water holes."],"variants":[{"name":"Crone","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cróin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Crón</i>’, a name from <i>crón</i> ‘swarthy’. Compare   Cronin  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>cron(e)</i> ‘crane’, Old English <i>cran</i>, <i>cron</i>, probably denoting someone with long legs. Compare   Crane  .","Scottish: shortened form   McCrone  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":1,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":32,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","descr